<seg id=1> U.S. Admits Air Raids Kill Hundreds Of Iraqi Civilians, English Reporter Says Bombs Fall On Non-military Targets </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> COMPILED FROM THE XINHUA NEWS AGENCY WIRE Washington, Feb. 13: The White House admitted today that air raids carried out by multilateral air forces on the Iraqi capital resulted in hundreds of civilian deaths, but insisted that they were aiming for military targets. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> A White House spokesperson said that the American government believes that this is "definitely a tragic outcome". </seg>
<seg id=4> However, he denounced Iraqi president Saddam Hussein for placing civilians within a military installation, putting them in danger. </seg>
<seg id=5> He said the U.S. believed the target was an Iraqi military command post. </seg>
<seg id=6> The installation "was covered and camouflaged to avoid reconnaissance, but the evidence shows that it was a military target". </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> COMPILED FROM THE XINHUA NEWS AGENCY WIRE London, February 13: A reporter for England's British Broadcasting Corporation stationed in Baghdad confirmed today that there was no indication that the bomb shelter destroyed by U.S. bombers was a military bunker. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> During the BBC television news broadcast the reporter refuted a statement by U.S. officials that the bomb shelter was actually a camouflaged military bunker. </seg>
<seg id=9> The reporter had visited the destroyed shelter, and estimated that about four hundred civilians had been killed. </seg>
</p>
